<item>
            <title>[GROOVY-414] Class names are not case sensitive on Mac OS X</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-414</link>
                <project id="12318123" key="GROOVY">Groovy</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;I cannot use a variable name that is the same as a class name, even if the case if different. For example, this will fail:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;snap = new Snap()&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;with this error:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;org.codehaus.groovy.syntax.SyntaxException: Cannot use a class expression on the left hand side of an assignment.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I believe this is because the default Mac OS file system supports mixed case filenames but file name searches are case insensitive. It appears that groovy searches the FS for a class that matches the token to determine if it is a class. But I think for Mac OS, even if it finds an FS match, it needs to do its own case sensitive comparison to determine if the token is indeed a class name.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>Mac OS X 10.3.2, java 1.4.2</environment>
        <key id="12812514">GROOVY-414</key>
